{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dbf75325-6836-4cee-b0b6-63f8cda4771d","content":"The current working directory is empty, so there's no repo-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance based on .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n---\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** The OS will write a core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If using macOS Catalina+**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps. You may need to:\n   ```bash\n   sudo /usr/libexec/reportcrash  # check it's running\n   ```\n\n5. **Inspect the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternatively**, check for Apple crash reports in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and may suffice for triage.\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, the core dump is a native dump — `lldb` is the primary analysis tool (not `dotnet-dump`). Ensure you have the `.dSYM` symbols alongside your binary for meaningful stack traces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f26c871-8951-4b9e-a94a-406b1f37c136","outputTokens":365,"requestId":"D808:14859A:34EA84D:39EEBEE:69FBF091"},"id":"ae659ebf-3ec3-462c-879f-808e35459040","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:53:32.292Z","parentId":"7df8171a-14c2-4eef-b55b-7694e66e381d"}
